Describe major motor patterns in the GI tract and their functions during fasting (migrating motor complex [MMC]) and during digestion 

 

Fasting 

The migrating motor complex is a pattern of electromechanical activity occurring during fasting. This is cyclical, and recurs every 1.5-2 hours. It consists of 4 main phases: 

1 -Smooth muscles are inactive, low number of action potentials and contractions for 45-60 mins 

2 -Peristaltic contractions begin to occur and increase in frequency, originating in stomach and propagating downward through small intestine for 30 mins 

3 -Rapid peristaltic contractions occur with pyloric sphincter remaining open, allows indigestible material to pass into the intestine for 15 mins 

4 -Transition period where systems resets to phase 1 

 

Digestion 

Peristalsis 

This is the contraction of circular muscle behind a bolus of food and relaxation of circular muscle in front of bolus. As such, the bolus is moved downward through the GIT at 2-30 cm/s depending on signals.  

 

Segmentation 

This involves the contraction of segments of circular muscle, breaking contents mechanically into separate lumps. Bolus movement is both forward and backward. 

 

 

 

 

List the multiple signals (neural, hormonal, mechanical) that stimulate and inhibit contraction in a smooth muscle cell of the GIT, and compare to skeletal muscle 

Neural 

A single neuron may have many connections to a unit of smooth muscle. Connections are known as varicosities/boutons. There may be an overlap of connections from separate neurons on a single muscle cell.  

Excitatory = ACH 

Inhibitory = Noradrenaline 

 

Mechanical 

Stretch-sensitive ion channels open to allow depolarisation, leading to smooth muscle contraction upon stretch.  

Physical deformation of the enteroendocrine cells along the length of the gut by food content can cause hormone release and contraction.  

 

Hormonal 

Hormones secreted along the GIT include: 

-Cholecystokinin increasing gallbladder and pancreas contraction, and increased intestinal motility 

-Gastrin increasing gastric acid and gastric + intestinal motility 

-Vasoactive intestinal peptide decreases activity of GIT sphincters, increasing motility 

-Somatostatin reduces pancreatic and gastric secretion 

-Serotonin increases gastric + intestinal motility on 5HT4 receptors, decreases on 5HT3 receptors 

 

 

Briefly describe the role of the enteric nervous system in the control of peristalsis 

There are 3 main types of neurons: Sensory, Motor, and Interneurons. The enteric nervous system is separated into the myenteric (between longitudinal and circular muscle) plexus, and the submucosal plexus.  

 

Myenteric plexus: Mainly for regulating GIT motility 

Submucosal plexus: Involved in sensing the luminal environment, regulating blood flow and controlling epithelial cell function 

 

Briefly describe the location and role of interstitial cells of Cajal 

Interstitial cells of Cajal (ICC) serve as electrical pacemakers in the GIT. They spontaneously generate rhythmic electrical waves which spread to the smooth muscle cells and cause contraction. These slow waves help organise the gut contractions into phasic peristalsis and segmentation contractions. Firing frequency differs along the length of the GIT: 

-5/min in stomach 

-10/min in duodenum 

-2/min in colon 

 

The main types of ICC are: 

-ICCMY or ICCMP - most active, present between longitudinal and circular muscle layers 

-ICCIM - present on the circular muscle layer 

-ICCSM - least active, found at interface of the submucosa and circular muscle layer 

 

Briefly describe how extrinsic nerves (sympathetic and parasympathetic) affect motor patterns 

Sympathetic = inhibitory. Sympathetic fibers terminate directly on the enteric plexus, with a few nerves terminating on the mucosal layer itself. Stimulation reduces motility, secretion, and enteric plexus activity. 

 

Parasympathetic = excitatory. Proximal GIT innervated from cranial parasympathetic fibers (Vagus), and distal GIT innervated from sacral parasympathetic fibers. Fibers terminate on the enteric plexuses only. Stimulation increases enteric plexus activity, motility, and secretion.  

 

Briefly describe how distention affects GI reflexes and alters response to other inputs 

Distention is a swelling of the GIT, with increased pressure. This pressure acts on stretch receptors which signal the flow of material through the GIT. Generally, activation of stretch receptors by normal food distention triggers increased peristalsis in the next part of the GIT. There are two types of GI reflexes. 

 

Intrinsic reflexes 

Irritation or distention of the mucosa triggers stimulation of the sensory afferent fibers to the local intrinsic ganglia of the enteric plexus. Efferent signals travel to relevant local cells, increasing secretion or motility. 

 

Extrinsic reflexes 

Extrinsic reflexes involve sensory afferent signals leaving the gut, and travelling to the sympathetic trunk, spinal cord, or brain.  

 

Short reflexes include: 

-Enterogastric reflex - stretch in duodenum shuts down gastric emptying 

-Ileogastric reflex - stretch in ileum shuts down gastric emptying 

-Gastrocolic reflex - stretch in stomach and duodenum increases peristalsis in the ileum and the opening of the ileocecal valve. Material flows into colon and triggers colon peristalsis.  

 

Long reflexes include: 

-Vomiting reflex 

-Pain reflex 

-Vagovagal reflexes eg esophageal stretch triggers relaxation of gastric smooth muscle in anticipation of bolus, stretch in stomach causes relaxation of gastric smooth muscle to increase carrying capacity 

-Defecation reflex 

 

Stretching of GIT muscles can impact the activity of ICC, leading to uncoordinated GIT contractions. Distention can also trigger the release of hormones from the enteroendocrine cells, affecting motility and secretion. 

 

Briefly describe how abnormal distention can cause GI pain and lead to abnormal motility 

Abnormal distention results in dysmotility of the GIT due to impaired ICC function. This leads to pain, cramping, vomiting, diarrhea, and constipation due to trapped contents. Note that abdominal distention can arise from other causes, eg heart failure leading to ascites.
